	<description>Use the <b>purge stack</b> <glossary tag="command">command</glossary> to purge a <glossary tag="main stack">main stack</glossary> from memory.<p></p><p><b>Parameters:</b></p><p>The <i>stack</i> is any valid main stack reference.</p><p></p><p><b>Comments:</b></p><p>The <b>delete stack</b> <glossary tag="command">command</glossary> has different effects, depending on whether the <i>stack</i> is a <glossary tag="main stack">main stack</glossary> or a <glossary tag="substack">substack</glossary>.</p><p></p><p>If the <i>stack</i> is a <glossary tag="main stack">main stack</glossary>, the <b>purge stack</b> <glossary tag="command">command</glossary> removes the <object tag="stack">stack</object> from memory. (Any unsaved changes are lost.) However, it does not remove it from the user's system. To delete a <glossary tag="main stack">main stack file</glossary>, use the <command tag="delete file">delete file</command> <glossary tag="command">command</glossary> instead.</p></description>
